
PWA — Progressive Web App
Right now, Clear is a website. Users open it in Chrome/Safari, see a browser address bar, and have to navigate to it every time. A PWA makes it behave like a native app installed on your phone — without going through the App Store or Play Store.

What "Installable" means
On Android (Chrome), after you visit the site, users get a banner or can tap "Add to Home Screen" from the browser menu. On iOS (Safari), it's manually via the share sheet → "Add to Home Screen".

Once installed:

An icon appears on the home screen — looks identical to any other app
Tapping it opens in standalone mode — no browser chrome, no address bar, no back/forward buttons. Looks 100% native.
It gets its own slot in the app switcher (the swipe-up tray on iPhone)
On Android it appears in Settings → Apps like a real installed app
On desktop (Chrome), it installs as a desktop app too
What's needed to make Clear installable
Three things:

1. manifest.json — A small JSON file that describes the app to the browser:

{
  "name": "Clear",
  "short_name": "Clear",
  "description": "Split it. Clear it.",
  "start_url": "/groups",
  "display": "standalone",
  "background_color": "#EFF6FF",
  "theme_color": "#0891B2",
  "icons": [
    { "src": "/icon-192.png", "sizes": "192x192", "type": "image/png" },
    { "src": "/icon-512.png", "sizes": "512x512", "type": "image/png" }
  ],
  "shortcuts": [
    { "name": "Add Expense", "url": "/groups?action=add", "icons": [...] }
  ]
}
Next.js has built-in support — you add this to app/manifest.ts and it's done.

2. HTTPS — Already satisfied by Vercel.

3. A Service Worker — A background script the browser installs alongside the app. This is what enables offline support, push notifications, and background sync. For just the "installable" part, it can be minimal (Next.js's next-pwa package handles this with near-zero config).

What changes for the user experience
Today (website)	After PWA
Open browser, type URL or find bookmark	Tap icon on home screen
Browser address bar always visible	Full screen, no chrome
No app in phone's app switcher	Appears in app switcher
Can't receive notifications when closed	Can receive push notifications
Loses state if signal drops	Can work offline (with service worker caching)
No home screen shortcuts	Long-press icon → "Add Expense", "My Balance"
What it does NOT do
Does not require App Store / Play Store submission
Does not give access to Bluetooth, NFC, or deep OS APIs (that's native-only)
Does not automatically update app store listings
On iOS, push notifications via PWA are limited — Apple only added support in iOS 16.4+, and only if the user has installed the PWA. Android has had full support for years.
Implementation effort for Clear
About 2–3 hours of work:

Add app/manifest.ts (Next.js 13+ native support, ~20 lines)
Generate icon assets at 192×512px (your existing cyan/teal brand)
Add next-pwa or a minimal public/sw.js for the service worker requirement
Set theme-color meta tag (changes the browser UI color on Android to match your cyan)
The offline caching and push notifications are separate, larger pieces — but the installable part alone is worth doing first since it immediately changes how users relate to the app.

